<h2 id="Scatter-Plots">Scatter Plots<a class="anchor-link" href="#Scatter-Plots">&#182;</a></h2><p>Remember that scatter plots plot a cloud of points representing the joint distribution of two variables. In Seaborn we can use either <code>sns.scatterplot()</code> or <code>sns.relplot()</code> and note that the default <code>kind</code> of <code>sns.relplot()</code> is scatter (think of <code>kind</code> as the type of plot you want to create). Also, <code>sns.relplot()</code> is considered a <code>Figure-level</code> interface, more on that later.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">


<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
        <div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Here we will plot tip against total_bill </span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">relplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;total_bill&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;tip&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">tips</span><span class="p">);</span> <span class="c1"># Note here x=&quot;&quot; and y=&quot;&quot; corresponds to the column names in the tips dataset </span>
</pre></div>

<p>Lets say we want to rename our x and y-axis to Total Bill and Tip, respectively and add a title to our plot. There are two possible ways to do this:</p>
<ol>
<li>Modifying the axes labels by calling <code>plt.subplots()</code> and use <code>sns.scatterplot()</code> to plot the data. </li>
<li>Modifying the axes labels returned when calling a figure level function in Seaborn*. </li>
</ol>
<p>Both ways are illustrated below, feel free to choose whatever style you prefer. Additionally, I've found the first way is helpful when you want to plot multiple plots in a grid. (Remember that Seaborn is built on Matplotlib.)</p>
<p>* With every <code>Figure-Level</code> interface, a <code>FacetGrid</code> object is returned which you can access to make edits to your plot. Learn more about <code>FacetGrid</code> <a href="http://seaborn.pydata.org/generated/seaborn.FacetGrid.html">here</a>, building structured multi-plot grids in Seaborn <a href="https://seaborn.pydata.org/tutorial/axis_grids.html">here</a> and</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">

    <div class="input_area">

<span class="n">fig</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">scatterplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;total_bill&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;tip&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">tips</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;Total Bill&quot;</span><span class="p">)</span>

<h2 id="Plotting-Categorical-Variables">Plotting Categorical Variables<a class="anchor-link" href="#Plotting-Categorical-Variables">&#182;</a></h2><p>The figure level interface for plotting categorical variables is <code>sns.catplot()</code>. We can think of different categorical plot kinds as belonging to three different families:</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Categorical scatterplots:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>sns.stripplot()</code> (with <code>kind="strip"</code>; the default)</li>
<li><code>sns.swarmplot()</code> (with <code>kind="swarm"</code>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>Categorical distribution plots:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>sns.boxplot()</code> (with <code>kind="box"</code>)</li>
<li><code>sns.violinplot()</code> (with <code>kind="violin"</code>)</li>
<li><code>sns.boxenplot()</code> (with <code>kind="boxen"</code>)</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>Categorical estimate plots:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>sns.pointplot()</code> (with <code>kind="point"</code>)</li>
<li><code>sns.barplot()</code> (with <code>kind="bar"</code>)</li>
<li><code>sns.countplot()</code> (with <code>kind="count"</code>)</li>
</ul>
<p>Below are some examples of each categorical plot.</p>
</li>
</ol>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">


<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
        <div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Categorical scatterplots</span>
<span class="c1"># Here we show how to plot total_bill within each day </span>
<span class="c1"># To prevent from overlapping try kind=&quot;swarm&quot;</span>
<span class="n">sns</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">catplot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;day&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">&quot;total_bill&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">tips</span><span class="p">);</span>
